<HEAD>Restructuring of Army Planned In Wake Of Corruption Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military chief plans a major restructuring of senior echelons of the army in the wake of allegations of widespread corruption and inefficiency, newspapers reported Sunday. Several major newspapers quoted unnamed sources as saying Chief of Staff Gen. <PERSON> Renato </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> announced the impending changes last Friday during a closed-door session of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s defense committee. The <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> Bulletin, The <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>, quoted de Villa as saying the shakeup would effect regional and division commanders. No date was given for the shakeup, but the papers said it was expected to be announced in a few weeks. The Inquirer quoted the defense committee chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON>, as telling his colleagues that if <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> did not move soon, he himself would open formal investigations into the allegations of corruption. The calls for a shakeup in the senior ranks have increased following a series of embarassing incidents. They include the November escape of Communist rebel commander <PERSON> Romulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON> from a <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> stockade; the takeover of a military headquarters by renegade policemen last January and the recent arrest of several police and military officers on car theft charges in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Last week, <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON> charged that unidentified generals and colonels were receiving thousands of dollars annually from criminal syndicates in return for shielding them from arrest. <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON> also challenged military claims that government forces have gained the upper hand in the 20-year war against the communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Ten senior officers, including army commander Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Mariano </PERSON> <PERSON> Adalem </PERSON>, are scheduled to retire this year. But the newspapers said the shakeup will affect many senior officers not scheduled for retirement.
