<HEAD>Boy Takes Up Mom's Challenge, Does Not Watch TV For Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with boy receiving award; pickup
6th graf pvs, ``It was ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemens </PERSON> awarded her 13-year-old son a $ 500 check Saturday night for fulfilling a dare to go a year without television. `` I'm just so proud of him,'' she said. `` That a teen-ager could do that is fantastic.'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON>, an eighth-grade student, described himself as a TV fanatic when his parents offered him the challenge of purging the tube from his life for 12 months. `` Bet you ca n't do that,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Lemens </PERSON> said she told him. Her husband, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>, upped the ante with a $ 500 reward if he gave up 365 days worth of his favorite cartoons, movies and situation comedies. The time trial ended at 8:39 p.m. Saturday. Mrs. <PERSON> Lemens </PERSON> said the absence of TV allowed her son more time for homework. While it did n't produce an improvement in his grades, she said, he has shown more interest in reading and non-television activities. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> said he plans to spend some of the money on stereo equipment and put the rest in the bank. He said the money was not the chief incentive. `` It was the challenge, not the money,'' he said. `` It helped me to motivate myself and realize that you can do anything you want if you try.'' The Journal of the American Medical Association estimates teen-agers watch an average of 21 hours of television a week. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> said he was above that average before the challenge. While the rest of his family watched television, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> said he would retreat to his room or to other diversions. `` I did my homework and read books, and in the summer I went outside and played,'' he said.
