EDITING; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Saturday doubled the bail of an accused cocaine trafficker who is a key figure in the federal investigation of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>. Chief U.S. District Court Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said new information provided Saturday by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's Office in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thomas </LOCATION> prompted the increase in bail from $ 100,000 set late Friday to $ 200,000. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said authorities had more than tripled their estimates of the amount of cocaine involved in two sales allegedly made last week by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. Earlier, <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gow </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> allegedly sold six to seven grams of the drug to agents on <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thomas </LOCATION> and would be charged with two counts of distributing cocaine. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> remained jailed in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thomas </LOCATION> on Saturday and was to appear in court there Monday for a bail hearing. The judge said federal prosecutors have 30 days to file charges. An <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> statement said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> was arrested Friday after allegedly attempting to sell agents the cocaine derivative `` crack'' twice last week on St. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. The 48-year-old St. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> resident allegedly sold five `` rocks'' to agents Thursday and another 20 on Friday just prior to his arrest, according to court reports and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> release. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said he had set bail at $ 100,000 over the telephone Friday on the `` bare-bones'' statement that both transactions involved a total 25 pieces of crack. But he said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's Office informed him Saturday the transaction actually involved 20 envelopes containing 85 pieces of crack. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report said that during the alleged buys, which it said were recorded on video and audio tape, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> told agents he could sell them `` pure cocaine'' that could be converted into crack. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> was the target of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> police investigation in December when a maid at a local hotel claimed that he offered her drugs in exchange for sex. Two district police officers went to the hotel to try to buy drugs from <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, but the drug buy was called off when the officers realized that <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> was visiting <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> at the time. A federal grand jury is now looking into the circumstances surrounding <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s visit to the hotel. A second investigation involving both <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> focuses on possible fraud in the city's $ 260,000 joint personnel project with the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>.
