<HEAD>Quake Aftershock At Grand Canyon; Quake Reported In Washington State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND CANYON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A moderate earthquake that shook Grand Canyon National Park on Saturday was followed by a moderate aftershock about nine hours later, but neither caused any damage or injury, officials said. Also late Saturday, an earthquake centered 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> was felt over a large area of western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> aftershock was recorded at a preliminary magnitude of 3.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale of ground motion at 2:18 a.m., said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey spokeswoman <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Jorgenson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The epicenter of the quake was near <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, about 60 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Flagstaff </LOCATION>, she said. Saturday's temblor at 5:41 p.m. had a preliminary magnitude of 4.0, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Finley </PERSON>, a Geological Survey spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` It was very quick,'' <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said of the Saturday quake. `` It probably lasted only five or six seconds. We could hear the glasses rattling in the cupboard, and you could feel the ground rumble and shudder.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, a moderate earthquake that shook the region at 10:42 p.m. was felt as far north as <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Jorgenson </PERSON> said. That temblor, with an epicenter in the Olympic Peninsula 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, was recorded with a preliminary magnitude of 4.4 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, she said. No damage or injuries were reported as a result of the quake, she added. The Richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Each increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. An earthquake of 3.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a `` major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a `` great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
