<HEAD>Lofty Light Bulb Changer Gets ``Weebles'' At Lincoln Memorial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaving desk-bound bureaucrats behind, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> has risen high in his government career, a man you can really look up to. He's the guy who changes light bulbs at the top of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument. Every week or so, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> climbs a ladder about 515 feet above ground to install a fresh bulb in the set of eight red airplane warning lights that blink unceasingly at the apex of the popular tourist attraction. Nothing to it, says <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, a 23-year veteran electrician for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. After all, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> works inside the monument, behind 18-inch-thick walls of granite and marble. He perches 15 feet above the observation deck atop an aluminum extension ladder held steady by an assistant. When he demonstrated his lofty job late last week, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> had <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, master <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> electrician for the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> region, as his supervisor. Although the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument sways slightly in a stiff wind, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> says the only time he feels queasy is when he climbs outdoor scaffolding with the `` weebles and wobbles'' to change light bulbs above the columns of the Lincoln Memorial. The bulbs that <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> replaces at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument are 500-watt spotlights that cost $ 70 apiece and last about a week or two. They flash on and off continually from four pairs of holes on each side of the pyramid-shaped monument peak. No airplane has ever struck the 555-foot <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument, which occupies airspace that is off-limits to planes landing or taking off at nearby <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. However, seven people have died in suicides or accidental falls down the monument's observation windows or elevator shaft since it was opened to the public on Oct. 9, 1888. Bars were installed in the narrow windows on the 500-foot level after they were used for the last two suicide leaps in 1926. Thick safety glass was installed later. A high metal grill was erected above the guard rail alongside the monument's 897 steps after the last suicide down the shaft occurred in 1949. The inner stairway was closed to the public in 1976, except for escorted tours downs the steps, because of vandalism and growing congestion. An eighth death occurred at the monument in December 1982 when police shot and killed <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, an anti-nuclear demonstrator who held the monument hostage for 10 hours claiming he would blow it up with dynamite. Ironically, no one was killed during the entire 36 years it took to build the monument.
