<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Agriculture Bjt   03-05 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Agriculture, Bjt,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Report on Agriculture Plays Down Importance of Leasing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet leadership, preparing for an important meeting on agriculture, has given short shrift to President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s campaign to lease more state-owned farmland to private groups. In last week's two-day Poliburo meeting, the 12-member ruling body referred to leasing as only one of many forms of management it said were necessary to ease chronic Soviet food shortages, Pravda reported Saturday. And in a speech in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Omsk </LOCATION>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s commission for agriculture, <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, also made only one mention of leasing. His speech was carried Friday by Pravda, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, reputedly a conservative force on the Politburo, opted instead for more traditional formulas calling for increased investment to better life in villages and to modernize farm machinery and technology. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in October said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership had decided to extend `` to the whole of agriculture'' an experiment that leased collective farmland to small groups and families, who would choose their crops and keep most of the profits. Farmers, he said in a speech, must again become `` complete masters'' of the land. With the exception of small garden plots tilled by individual citizens, all farmland is state-owned in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Since the bloody drive launched by dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in 1929 to eliminate the independent peasantry, the mainstays of the Soviet agricultural system have been the `` kolkhozes,'' or collective farms, and the `` sovkhozes,'' or state-owned farms. A leasing system runs counter to Marxist-Leninist theory, which holds that a socialist form of ownership, such as the collective farms, is a higher and more efficient form of organization than private farming. Any changes would threaten the entrenched bureaucracy that runs the collective and state-owned farms and the sprawling superministry of agriculture. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the son of a Russian peasant, has not called for the dismantlement of collective or state farms, which have been run for decades like factories, with orders from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on what and when to plant handed down to the wage earners who work the fields. But he said in October the practice of paying them `` unearned money'' had to stop. In the past 20 years, he said, capital investment in the agriculture sector rose 140 percent, but production increased only 41 percent. In contrast, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said, dairy farms run on the leasing system produce more milk per cow than ordinary farms. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> acknowledged in January that the leasing campaign ran into opposition from bureaucrats and collective farmers, who view those who enroll in it as latter-day descendants of the `` kulaks,'' or rich peasants. `` Leasing is proceeding with difficulty, and thus many people, the innovators, are being called kulaks and <ORGANIZATION> Rockefellers </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` Many people, especially the lazy, do n't like the fact that leasing is destroying the ... habits of the years of stagnation, when you could get a good salary no matter how you worked.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said a law was being drafted to prepare the interests of farmers who entered into long-term leases. The Politburo, preparing for a meeting of the party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on agriculture later this month, said it supported the creation of `` multiple forms of ownership and types of management _ of kolkhozes, sovkhozes, agro-industrial amalgamations, processing enterprises, leasees, members of cooperatives, leasing collectives, farmsteads, personal farmplots of citizens,'' Pravda said In <LOCATION> Omsk </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> used similar language, calling for the `` spread of different organizational forms of production, based on self-accounting, the brigade and lease relations, cooperatives and also the democratization of management on all levels,'' Pravda said. The Politburo report did not say when the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> would meet again, but at its last plenum in January, the 300-plus member body announced it would hold a plenary session March 15-16.
