<HEAD>Three Mayoral Candidates Have Democratic Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The front-runner for next month's mayoral election is a Democrat, his closest pursuer was a Democrat as recently as December, and the No. 3 man in the race was Democratic county chairman just 18 months ago. An out-of-towner might ask what these guys _ <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and former county chairman-turned Republican <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> _ are fighting about? But Chicagoans are n't surprised. `` When you have only one functioning party choosing one candidate, the other guys get blocked, then frustrated, then go off on their own and call themselves something else,'' explains <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Royko </PERSON>, a veteran political observer and columnist for the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a black, ran as a Democrat when he was elected alderman and is now running for mayor as an independent. <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> entered the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> primary at the last minute as a write-in candidate, and even though he got 80 percent of the white vote in his unsuccessful independent mayoral challenge in 1987, he is regarded as third in the race now. The city's last Republican mayor was <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> `` Big Bill'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, a three-term mayor so brazen about his alliance with gangsters that his portrait hung in the headquarters of the <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> gang. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> was eased out in 1931 by <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> `` Pushcart Tony'' <PERSON> Cermak </PERSON>, credited with bringing to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> the modern political machine: a coalition of ethnic voters bound by the principle of self-interest _ everybody gets something. What followed was a succession of politicians as diverse as <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s father, the late <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> _ the last of the big-city `` bosses'' who died in 1976 _ and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, a reformer whose 1983 election as the city's first black mayor and whose death just months into his second term in 1987 altered the course of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` If the old man -LRB- <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> -RRB- were alive, there's a lot about the party he would n't recognize, even if his son winds up at the top of it,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and author of `` Himself,'' a biography of the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. `` In his day, a Democrat was a Democrat first and whatever else he was came second.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> changed that by winning with little more than a single racial bloc, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. The town is about 40 percent white, 40 percent black and 20 percent Hispanic and other minorities. `` And what you see now, essentially, are three men _ two white and one black _ relying on the same strategy, trying to do essentially the same thing,'' he added. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s 1983 election came after a racially charged campaign. But his ability to govern fairly eased the fears of many whites who opposed him, and he was re-elected in 1987 with significantly less strife. The younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> last week became the first white to oust an incumbent black mayor in a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> city by defeating <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who filled in after <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s death. But their primary campaign was surprisely free of rancor and appeals to