<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Prepare for East-West Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers from 35 countries meet Monday for East-West conventional arms control talks that may bring sweeping reductions in troops and military hardware from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to the Urals. During a three-day conference at <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s former <LOCATION> Hofburg </LOCATION> imperial palace, the ministers also will review prospects for a conference to build confidence and security between East and West bloc nations of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The ministers were in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in January to wrap up the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> follow-up Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which agreed on the new arms control talks and landmark human rights provisions for the Soviet bloc. A new man on the scene this time is Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who will meet Tuesday with his Soviet counterpart, <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. They are to use their <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> sojourn to hold bilateral talks both sides hope will lay the groundwork for successful discussions in coming months. Negotiations on reducing conventional troops and arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will be conducted between the 16 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries and seven members of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. Talks on new confidence and security building measures involve all 35 countries, including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and all European countries except self-isolated <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. The talks start Thursday. Western hopes are based on reduced <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> tensions and the successful conclusion of Intermediate Nuclear Forces talks leading to the destruction of the superpowers' intermediate-range nuclear missiles. The Soviets and most of their allies also are showing a willingness to reduce military spending in favor of more and better consumer goods. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in December gave the new talks a boost when he announced a unilateral reduction of half a million Soviet troops in 1989-90, 50,000 of them in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Since then, all <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations except <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> have announced plans to trim their militaries. The arms talks will cover conventional armed forces and armaments and equipment based on land. Naval forces and chemical and nuclear weapons will not be negotiated. The Western alliance is seeking reductions of more than 50 percent from the Soviets and their allies to offset what it says is the Soviet bloc's 2-1 superiority in tanks and artillery, a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> source said in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> this week. In return, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> offers to cut its artillery, tanks and some other mobile weapons by 5 percent to 10 percent in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the source said. `` Since we are convinced that we ... -LRB- are -RRB- pretty much at the minimum of our defense, this means for our military people a significant sacrifice,'' the source told reporters at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said on Friday the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> wants to eliminate imbalances, especially in offensive weapons, `` to restructure the armed forces of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> so as to give an absolutely defensive character to troops and armaments during cutbacks.'' He also said verification, a chief obstacle to the failed 15-year talks on cutting troops and tanks in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, could be surmounted because of better monitoring abilities and more exchange of information. Under new <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> proposals to be submitted in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, there should be no more than 40,000 main battle tanks _ 20,000 for each side. Artillery pieces should be kept to 33,000 and armored troop carriers to 55,000 _ equally shared between the two sides. The other talks are a continuation of the 35-nation <ORGANIZATION> Stockholm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, which in 1986 formally adopted the first East-West security agreement of the decade, an accord designed to reduce the risk of an accidental war in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> source said the Western alliance will propose an annual exchange of information concerning military organization, manpower and equipment involving all participants, improved observation and improved access for accredited personnel dealing with military matters and media.
