he <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>'s, where chickens and babies run through dirt courtyards past graffiti-covered walls. `` Thank God my other brother, <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON>, was n't here. They were just taking anybody they could. They took away good boys from this building,'' said <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, 22, sitting on a bed with her mother. On the wall above them were bullet holes, proof of fierce gun battles between army units posted on a hill above the complex and snipers inside the building. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> and his father, <PERSON> Abdon </PERSON>, work as hospital janitors and were not home when soldiers searched the building Friday, said <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>. She said fighting had quieted down since then, but sporadic firing continued through Saturday. Officials cut off electricity to the building, but Mrs. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said, `` we ca n't leave because if the military comes again and nobody's home, they'll destroy our home.'' `` We've been sleeping in the hall all week,'' she said. She said she did n't know who the snipers were. `` We can see the boys firing out the windows. But who knows where they're getting their weapons?'' she said. Military spokesmen have said snipers were been using pistols and Belgian FAL automatic rifles, which are also used by the army. `` I do n't know how this is going to end,'' <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said. `` I think the government is going to send in an assault. There's going to be a response, and it's going to end in a massacre Because when the army comes in, they do n't have good intentions.''
