<HEAD>California Supreme Court To Take Up Insurance Revolt Proposition
103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rate-cutting ax that voters dropped on the auto insurance industry four months ago has produced a confusion of government hearings and legal counterattacks by insurers, but no relief for consumers. In fact, millions of Californians have seen their rates go up while voter-approved rate rollbacks remain frozen by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> pending review of legal challenges filed by insurers. This week, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will begin considering whether to unleash Proposition 103. The court is scheduled to hear arguments Tuesday but has 90 days to rule. The measure, if upheld as constitutional, would lower property and auto insurance rates by an immediate 20 percent below November 1987 rates in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. It would require an additional 20 percent cut in auto insurance rates for good drivers next November. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION>, said the industry believes that the court `` ultimately will find that Proposition 103 is unconstitutional and that it will overturn the complete initiative.'' If so, Fountain predicted, lawmakers would launch into a flurry of proposals to establish `` reasonable rates and cost controls,'' with the guidance of the industry. `` We have learned that you can not ignore the voters.'' Insurers' assessment of what will happen if the court upholds the measure has n't changed much since pre-election days, when they predicted many companies would just pull out of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> market, said Fountain. Proposition 103 author <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenfield </PERSON> said that if the measure is upheld, the insurance market will remain calm if insurers cooperate. If it is overturned, `` we'll be back on the ballot with ` Son of 103,''' he said. `` We're glad the court is moving toward a decision,'' he said. `` It's extremely important to decide quickly because we have all these insurance companies out there taking advantage of the stay by increasing rates at unconscionable levels.'' Drivers who expected their rates to go down following passage of the measure have had an unwelcome surprise. For example, the largest auto insurer in the state, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION>, said it is raising rates an average 9.6 percent this year because of underwriting losses not entirely offset by investment income. The action has been challenged by the state. In other cases, drivers are just now paying, as their policies come up for renewal, rate increases that went into effect last year. About 70 of some 400 companies selling auto insurance in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> raised rates more than 10 percent in 1988, state officials say. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s insurance war erupted as rates skyrocketed, particularly in the cities. Insurers in part blamed trial attorneys for waging lengthy court battles in an attempt to win big settlements. In turn, attorneys said insurers were just seeking bigger profits. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, torn by the powerful lobbies of the insurers and lawyers, was virtually paralyzed. <PERSON> Rosenfield </PERSON>, a disciple of consumer advocate <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, led a citizen campaign that placed Proposition 103 on the November ballot. The insurance industry poured more than $ 60 million into the battle against the measure. Though outgunned financially, the Nader-backed measure won a slim victory, with 51 percent of the vote. Consumer advocates in other states hailed the passage of Proposition 103 as an indication that the issue, already simmering in many areas, could come to a boil elsewhere. Reacting to the lawsuits filed by the insurance industry, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> suspended all provisions of Proposition 103, pending its review. Later, it let all provisions but the rate rollbacks go into effect while it considered the measure. Despite the court suspension of Proposition 103 provisions, there has been no cease-fire in the insurance war. State Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> insurance committee, has accused several insurance companies of violating the spirit of the proposition. He joined other lawmakers in introducing bills designed to make insurers live under the spirit of Proposition 103 until all its provisions become effective. After the state <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> challenged a plan to refer new customers to a higher-priced subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION>, which insures 2.8 million drivers in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, announced it would boost its rates instead. The <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has set hearings this month for both <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION>'s earlier policy-switching plan and its subsequent rate-hike proposal. The department has prohibited 11 companies with smaller customer rosters from refusing to renew auto insurance policies after Proposition 103 passed. Insurance Commissioner <PERSON> Roxani </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON> said the companies violated provisions of Proposition 103 that restrict insurers' authority to refuse to renew auto policies
