<FIRST>r w AM-ConsumerAgenda     03-05 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Agenda,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Dozen Groups Outlines Rules Ranging from Bunk Beds to Garage
Doors</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 6 p.m. EST - time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY B. DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coalition of two dozen consumer advocacy groups, medical associations, insurance companies and trade associations on Sunday outlined an ambitious agenda of safety and health proposals extending to regulation of bunk beds and garage door openers. The Coalition for Consumer Health and Safety said in a report on its yearlong agenda project that injuries were the fourth leading cause of death in 1987, behind heart disease, cancer and strokes, and that when `` products broadly'' such as food, cigarettes and alcohol are considered, `` then they also play a part in nearly all of the 10 leading causes of death in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The Statistical Abstract of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says that accidents in 1983 killed about 92,500 people out of slightly more than 2 million deaths. Insurance companies and their customers must pay many costs of accidents _ the report said drug and alcohol abuse cost auto insurers $ 12 billion a year, life insurers $ 4 billion and health insurers $ 27 billion. The group made recommendations, many of them familiar, in seven areas _ motor vehicles, home products, food, indoor air pollution, cigarettes, alcohol and AIDS. Among them:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>AUTOS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The group called for all states to pass mandatory seat belt laws, stronger auto side impact standards, rear-seat shoulder belts, encouragement of full-width front-seat airbags and the extension of federal auto safety standards to the increasingly popular vans and utility vehicles which currently meet the less stringent truck standards. It said anti-lock brakes should be required on trucks and strongly considered for cars.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOME PRODUCTS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 New powers were urged for the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. In specifics, the coalition called for putting amusement parks under jurisdiction of the commission, which now may regulate only traveling carnivals; for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to require development of a cigarette fire safety standard; for development of child-resistant disposable cigarette lighters; for a ban on the sale of fireworks and for extension of requirements for smoke detectors and sprinkler systems. Garage door openers have killed 34 children since 1982, typically by pinning the child to the ground when the child activates the door-closing mechanism and tries to get out of the garage before the door closes, the group said. It urged development of a standard requiring an automatic reversing mechanism that would prevent such accidents. Bunk beds killed 72 children between 1972 and 1987, often by entrapment and strangulation, the coalition said in arguing for a mandatory standard to replace the current, ill-observed voluntary standard.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>INDOOR AIR</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The group called for more research on contaminants and ways to deal with them, including product standards for devices such as heaters and stoves that might contribute to the problem. It said the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> should coordinate activities of all government agencies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FOOD</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal and state governments should undertake `` extensive public nutrition education campaigns'' to promote healthy diets and should clarify and strengthen nutrition labeling requirements. Half of what's in the supermarket carries no label information, and `` The problem of incomplete and confusing labeling is compounded for people on restrictive diets such as those suffering from diabetes, hypertension and high cholesterol.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CIGARETTES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Governments should restrict smoking in public places, encourage employers to develop non-smoking policies, enforce age restrictions on cigarette purchase and increase education on the evils of smoking, which causes 390,000 deaths a year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ALCOHOL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The group called for label warnings of the risks of drinking, lists of ingredients and calorie content on labels, and, since `` alcohol advertising overwhelms public health efforts,'' more radio and television commercials to spotlight the risks and a prohibition on sports figures in pro-drinking ads.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>AIDS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 As the number of AIDS cases grows, it will strain public resources, and thus it is a consumer issue, the coalition argued. It called for greatly increased educational efforts, particularly those aimed at changing high-risk sexual practices.
</TEXT>
