/PERSON> <PERSON> Martinyuk </PERSON>, won applause for joining the call to open government archives. But the audience was less receptive when he said the party was a victim of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Martinyuk </PERSON> said 94 of the 120 members of the Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s time were `` repressed.'' In answer to questions from the crowd, <PERSON> Shevchenko </PERSON> claimed to have no power to free the four activists arrested 10 days ago, but promised to investigate and protest if the charge _ hooliganism _ proves false. `` We have a Soviet society of laws,'' he said, using a favorite phrase of reformers. When the prosecutor said Ukrainian officials already abide by the law, some crowd members laughed.
