<HEAD>Snakebite Victim Resting Comfortably, But Remains In Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A snake-venom researcher bitten by a deadly viper rested comfortably Sunday while doctors considered whether to treat him with antivenins from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, a hospital spokesman said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>, 78, remained in serious but stable condition at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> after being bitten on the left hand Tuesday by a Pakistani pit viper, also known as a saw-scaled viper, said hospital spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON>. `` Mr. <PERSON> Haast </PERSON> is resting very comfortably, eating and chatting with friends,'' <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said. `` He's just in danger, if you will.'' <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Serpentarium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> at the university's Research Park, has been bitten 148 times by snakes and is immune to the venom of dozens of reptiles. But he had no immunity to the viper's bite and checked himself into the hospital Wednesday. The saw-scaled viper's venom attacks its victim's ability to produce fibrinogen, an element of blood that regulates coagulation. A lack of fibrinogen can cause uncontrolled bleeding. <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said the level of <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s fibrinogen had been improving slightly although it remained `` dangerously low'' Sunday. Doctors were replacing <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s fibrinogen with transfusions and it appeared his system had begun to produce it again, <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s blood was being analyzed every four hours, and that by late Saturday his fibrogen level was about one-third of normal. On Wednesday, he said, `` for all intents and purposes -LRB- it was -RRB- at zero.'' <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s plight prompted an effort by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Studdernt </PERSON>, special assistant to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, to coordinate the acquisition of antivenins from the three nations and expedite shipment to <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said antivenins from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> had arrived, but he did not know if the one from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had. The antivenin from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was more specifically made to counteract venom from the species of viper that bit <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>, he said. However, he said doctors were `` very leery about giving medication to someone from a source about which we know very little about.'' Antivenins are made from horse serum and can cause negative side effects such as lung and kidney problems, he said. `` We want to emphasize the fact that we're grateful to everyone who went to such great lengths to get the antivenin,'' <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said. `` The decision on whether to use them or not will be based on Mr. <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s condition. Hopefully we wo n't have to use them.'' <PERSON> Haast </PERSON> had been treated earlier with antivenins from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> and from a lab in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said Saturday he had not been given antivenins for about 24 hours He said doctors also had contacted scientists and physicans in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> to discuss treatment. `` It's a special kind of snake, with a special kind of poison, and the immunology is complicated,'' <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said. `` Our physicians are n't just winging it on their own.'' <PERSON> Studdert </PERSON> said the Iranian government apparently did not interfere with the shipment of the antivenin despite the strained relations between the two nations. Iranian leader <PERSON> Ayatolla </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has often called the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the `` great Satan.'' The Pakistani pit viper is one of 1,000 exotic, poisonous snakes <PERSON> Haast </PERSON> keeps at the laboratory, where their venom is extracted for sale to universities and health organizations for research and the manufacture of antivenins.
