<HEAD>New Sunday Edition Of New York Post Stretches For Brains And Brawn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> fired the latest salvo in the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s four-way newspaper war, trying to lure both the brainy and the brawny in a new Sunday edition combining savvy with sports. The tabloid, which has a third-place circulation of about 600,000, pushed its eclectic new image with a front-page article on <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinbrenner </PERSON> by literary journalist <PERSON> Nora </PERSON> <PERSON> Ephron </PERSON>. If sophistication was not a draw, there was <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> the Menace and Uncle Art's Funland, in color. The cartoons formerly ran in black and white on Saturdays. For those hooked on the weekday Post's fare of politics and crime, the front page headlined an exclusive in three-inch letters: `` Koch ` Hit Men' Booted,'' on the secret deportation of two Colombians believed to have been sent to kill Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>. And there were sports, sports and more sports. Post President <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> pushed the button that started the presses for the Sunday edition of the nation's oldest continuously published daily at 7:55 p.m. Saturday. The Tuxedo-clad <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> uncorked a bottle of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> champagne and poured glasses for cheering pressmen in ink-stained coveralls and paper hats. Later, <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> led them into the area where 575,000 Sunday papers were bundled and packed off for delivery. Publisher <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON> handed out free copies of the paper Sunday to travelers arriving at La Guardia airport. A year ago, <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON>, a developer, saved the 188-year-old newspaper from extinction by buying it from media mogul <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> for $ 37 million. <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> threatened to close the money-losing paper if he could n't find a buyer. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> now competes seven days a week for readers and advertisers with the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> edition of Newsday, the <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> daily. The Post is third in the city circulation race, trailing the News -LRB- 1,281,706 -RRB- and the Times -LRB- 1,038,829 -RRB- and leading <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Newsday -LRB- 176,043 in the city, and 706,440 overall -RRB-, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circulations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> is trying to lure the more than 300,000 people who read both the daily <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, but who may not want to carry home the slicker Sunday version of his paper, said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lois </PERSON>, who created an advertising campaign for the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. The Post, which like many newspapers expects to obtain most of its advertising revenue from its Sunday edition, `` is fully booked with ads for the next four weeks,'' said <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> said he expects to spend $ 22 million to $ 25 million on the Sunday Post in the first year. He said it would be months before he knows if the move has paid off. Many media analysts have said they are skeptical that the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market can support a fourth Sunday newspaper.
